{"title_page": "Wincanton plc", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=January 2017}}\n{{Use British English|date=January 2017}}\n{{Infobox company\n| name = Wincanton plc\n| logo = Wincanton.svg\n| logo_size = 200px\n| type = [[Public company|Public]]\n| traded_as = {{LSE|WIN}}\n| industry = [[Logistics]]\n| foundation = 1925\n| location = [[Chippenham]], United Kingdom\n| key_people = Dr Martin Read MBE ([[Chairman]])<br>James Wroath ([[chief executive officer|CEO]])\n| products = Logistics<br />[[Supply chain management]]\n| revenue = [[Pound sterling|\u00a3]]1,171.9 million (2018)<ref name=ar>{{cite web|url=https://www.wincanton.co.uk/media/2078/wincanton-ara-2018-interactive.pdf|title=Annual Report 2018|publisher=Wincanton plc|accessdate=22 June 2018}}</ref>\n| operating_income = \u00a344.4 million (2018)<ref name=ar/>\n| net_income = \u00a331.2 million (2018)<ref name=ar/>\n| num_employees = \n| homepage = [http://www.wincanton.co.uk/ www.wincanton.co.uk]\n}}\n\n'''Wincanton plc''' is a [[United Kingdom|British]] provider of [[logistics]] with its origins in milk haulage. The company provides transport and logistics services including specialist automated high bay, high capacity warehouses, and [[supply chain management]] for businesses.<ref name=\"hb2010\">{{cite web|url=http://www.wincanton.co.uk/about-us/the-wincanton-journey/|title=Wincanton Journey|last=|first=|date=|website=|publisher=Wincanton Plc|access-date=|accessdate=2016-08-02}}</ref> It also provides [[Containerization|container]] transportation and storage, [[Warehouse|warehousing]] [[solution]]s and related services, such as health and safety, IT services and people transition to numerous industries.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.wincanton.co.uk/services/|title=Reliable, scalable, collaborative and flexible supply chain services|website=www.wincanton.co.uk|access-date=2016-08-02}}</ref>\n\nWincanton's specialist markets include [[retail]], consumer goods, [[construction]], [[dairy]], defence, industrial, [[fuel]]s and energy.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.wincanton.co.uk/sectors/|title=Supply Chain & Logistic Sector Experts - Wincanton|website=www.wincanton.co.uk|access-date=2016-08-02}}</ref> It is listed on the [[London Stock Exchange]], and is a former constituent of the [[FTSE 250 Index]]. \n\n==History==\nWincanton was founded in 1925, as '''Wincanton Transport & Engineering Ltd''', a subsidiary of the [[West Surrey Central Dairy Company]], a company which has since been known as [[Cow & Gate]], [[Unigate]] and then [[Uniq plc|Uniq]].<ref name=\"hb2008\">{{cite web|url=http://www.wincanton.co.uk/about-us/the-wincanton-journey/|title=Wincaton Journey|last=|first=|date=|website=|publisher=Wincanton Plc|access-date=|accessdate=2016-08-02}}</ref>\n\nIn the 1970s, Wincanton diversified into new market sectors including [[petroleum]] and developed temperature controlled operations for the [[transport]]ation of [[food]] stuffs and refrigerated goods.<ref name=\"wincanton.co.uk\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.wincanton.co.uk/about-us/the-wincanton-journey/|title=Wincanton {{!}} 1925 to today, follow Wincanton's history|website=www.wincanton.co.uk|access-date=2016-08-02}}</ref> In the 1990s, Wincanton merged with [[Uniq plc|Unigate]] Chilled Distribution, and entered the [[Retail|retail market]], through the acquisition of Glass Glover in February 1993.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.heraldscotland.com/news/12619743.Unigate_buys_Glass_Glover/|title=Unigate buys Glass Glover|date=16 February 1993|publisher=Herald Scotland|accessdate=22 June 2018}}</ref> In March 2001, Wincanton plc [[Demerger|demerged]] from Uniq, and was listed on the [[London Stock Exchange]].<ref name=\"wincanton.co.uk\"/>\n\nIn November 2015, Wincanton sold its [[records management]] business (WRM) to [[Restore plc|Restore]] for approximately \u00a355.7m to reduce its average net [[Debt|indebtedness]], and allow room for growth.<ref name=\"Reports and presentations\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.wincanton.co.uk/investors/reports-and-presentations/|title=Reports and presentations|website=www.wincanton.co.uk|access-date=2016-08-02}}</ref> In February 2016, Wincanton partnered with [[Magnet Kitchens]] to produce forty four new double decker [[Articulated trailer bus|articulated trailers]] which was an investment of \u00a32 million.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.wincanton.co.uk/media-centre/press-releases/wincanton-helps-magnet-cut-carbon-emissions/|title=Partnership pioneers unique double decker articulated trailers|website=www.wincanton.co.uk|access-date=2016-08-02}}</ref> \n\nIn March 2016, Wincanton launched EnergyLink, a network based in the United Kingdom to support greater flexibility in delivery services for the [[Energy industry|energy sector]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.wincanton.co.uk/media-centre/press-releases/wincanton-launches-new-energy-sector-services/|title=Wincanton launches new energy sector services|website=www.wincanton.co.uk|access-date=2016-08-02}}</ref> \n\nIn April 2016, Wincanton gained further growth of its operations at the [[Port of Southampton]] after moving to a new base and investing in new equipment, supported by extra [[Rail transport|rail]] capacity. <ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.wincanton.co.uk/media-centre/press-releases/wincanton-grows-at-port-of-southampton/|title=Wincanton logistics expands at Port of Southampton|website=www.wincanton.co.uk|access-date=2016-08-02}}</ref> In June 2016, Wincanton renewed its distribution deal with [[Sainsbury's|J Sainsburys PLC]] for an additional five years. The business has been a customer of Wincanton for the past twenty one years.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.londonstockexchange.com/exchange/news/market-news/market-news-detail/WIN/12854115.html|title=Contract Renewal with Sainsbury's - RNS - London Stock Exchange|website=www.londonstockexchange.com|access-date=2016-08-02}}</ref>\n\nIn July 2016, Wincanton renewed a contract with [[The Co-operative Group]] for a further five years, which brings the contract to twenty five years. As part of the agreement, around seven hundred staff of Wincanton and a fleet of more than five hundred vehicles will support the Co Op, by making around 130k journeys each year to as many as 1,000 stores of the Co-op across the United Kingdom.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://bdaily.co.uk/industrials/26-07-2016/the-co-op-signs-five-year-logistics-deal-with-wincanton-plc/|title=The Co-op signs five-year logistics deal with Wincanton plc|last=Bell|first=Richard|access-date=2016-08-02}}</ref> \n\nIn October 2019, Wincanton plc expressed an interest in merging with [[Eddie Stobart Logistics|Eddie Stobart]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www-cityam-com.cdn.ampproject.org/v/s/www.cityam.com/wincanton-pursues-possible-merger-with-eddie-stobart/amp/?amp_js_v=a2&amp_gsa=1&usqp=mq331AQCKAE%3D#aoh=15734962302273&referrer=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.google.com&amp_tf=From%20%251%24s&ampshare=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.cityam.com%2Fwincanton-pursues-possible-merger-with-eddie-stobart%2F|title=Wincanton pursues possible merger with Eddie Stobart|date=18 October 2019|publisher=City AM|accessdate=11 November 2019}}</ref> Wincanton, later withdrew their offer, saying that it had \u201cyet to receive full disclosure of the information requested to enable it to complete its due diligence exercise\u201d.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.logisticsmanager.com/wincanton-withdraws-eddie-stobart-interest/|title= Wincanton withdraws Eddie Stobart interest|publisher=Logistics Manager|date=25 November 2019|accessdate=25 November 2019}}</ref>\n\n== Headquarters ==\nThe company's origins are in [[Wincanton]], [[Somerset]], although the head office is now based in Methuen Park, [[Chippenham]], [[Wiltshire]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.google.co.uk/maps/place/Wincanton/@51.4945473,-1.60133,10z/data=!4m8!1m2!2m1!1swincanton+plc!3m4!1s0x0:0x7561bd1a219b0763!8m2!3d51.445823!4d-2.1469688|title=Google Maps|website=Google Maps|access-date=2016-08-02}}</ref>\n\n==Operations==\nWincanton currently directly employs in the region of 20,000 people across the United Kingdom and Ireland through a network of over two hundred sites.<ref name=\"ReferenceA\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.wincanton.co.uk/about-us/wincanton-overview/|title=Wincanton {{!}} transport, storage, supply chain innovation|website=www.wincanton.co.uk|access-date=2016-08-02}}</ref> As of 2016, the Wincanton fleet comprises over 3,400 [[vehicle]]s including conventional [[truck]]s and trailers, as well as a range of specialist equipment including skeletal trailers, tankers and [[Heavy equipment|construction vehicles]].<ref name=\"ReferenceA\"/>\n\n== Services ==\nWincanton offers road transport and [[Distribution (business)|distribution]], container [[logistics]], specialist transport to [[Construction|construction sites]], tankers for all liquid and powder products, including [[Lubricant|petroleum and lubricants]], [[Delivery (commerce)|home delivery]] and [[fleet management]] and vehicle maintenance through its subsidiary business, Pullman Fleet Services.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.wincanton.co.uk/services/transport/|title=Transport and Logistics Management - Transport Companies UK|website=www.wincanton.co.uk|access-date=2016-08-02}}</ref> Wincanton offers dedicated and shared user warehousing, [[Bonded warehouse|bonded warehousing]] and other services. \n\nThese include co packing, [[automation]], eFulfilment, off quay [[solution]]s, returns management, [[recycling]] and [[Packaging and labeling|packaging]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.wincanton.co.uk/services/warehouse-solutions/|title=Warehousing logistics and services from Wincanton|website=www.wincanton.co.uk|access-date=2016-08-02}}</ref> Wincanton also offers integrated [[IT service management|IT services]], change management and people transition ([[Transfer of Undertakings (Protection of Employment) Regulations 2006|TUPE]]) services.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.wincanton.co.uk/services/value-added-services/|title=Value Added Services - Value Chain at Wincanton|website=www.wincanton.co.uk|access-date=2016-08-02}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Wincanton Plc}}\n[[Category:Companies based in Wiltshire]]\n[[Category:Logistics companies of the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:Transport operators of the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:Business services companies established in 1925]]\n[[Category:1925 establishments in England]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=January 2017}}\n{{Use British English|date=January 2017}}\n{{Infobox company\n| name = Wincanton plc\n| logo = Wincanton.svg\n| logo_size = 200px\n| type = [[Public company|Public]]\n| traded_as = {{LSE|WIN}}\n| industry = [[Logistics]]\n| foundation = 1925\n| location = [[Chippenham]], United Kingdom\n| key_people = Dr Martin Read MBE ([[Chairman]])<br>James Wroath ([[chief executive officer|CEO]])\n| products = Logistics<br />[[Supply chain management]]\n| revenue = [[Pound sterling|\u00a3]]1,171.9 million (2018)<ref name=ar>{{cite web|url=https://www.wincanton.co.uk/media/2078/wincanton-ara-2018-interactive.pdf|title=Annual Report 2018|publisher=Wincanton plc|accessdate=22 June 2018}}</ref>\n| operating_income = \u00a344.4 million (2018)<ref name=ar/>\n| net_income = \u00a331.2 million (2018)<ref name=ar/>\n| num_employees = \n| homepage = [http://www.wincanton.co.uk/ www.wincanton.co.uk]\n}}\n\n'''Wincanton plc''' is a [[United Kingdom|British]] provider of [[logistics]] with its origins in milk haulage. The company provides transport and logistics services including specialist automated high bay, high capacity warehouses, and [[supply chain management]] for businesses.<ref name=\"hb2010\">{{cite web|url=http://www.wincanton.co.uk/about-us/the-wincanton-journey/|title=Wincanton Journey|last=|first=|date=|website=|publisher=Wincanton Plc|access-date=|accessdate=2016-08-02}}</ref> It also provides [[Containerization|container]] transportation and storage, [[Warehouse|warehousing]] [[solution]]s and related services, such as health and safety, IT services and people transition to numerous industries.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.wincanton.co.uk/services/|title=Reliable, scalable, collaborative and flexible supply chain services|website=www.wincanton.co.uk|access-date=2016-08-02}}</ref>\n\nWincanton's specialist markets include [[retail]], consumer goods, [[construction]], [[dairy]], defence, industrial, [[fuel]]s and energy.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.wincanton.co.uk/sectors/|title=Supply Chain & Logistic Sector Experts - Wincanton|website=www.wincanton.co.uk|access-date=2016-08-02}}</ref> It is listed on the [[London Stock Exchange]], and is a former constituent of the [[FTSE 250 Index]]. \n\n==History==\nWincanton was founded in 1925, as '''Wincanton Transport & Engineering Ltd''', a subsidiary of the [[West Surrey Central Dairy Company]], a company which has since been known as [[Cow & Gate]], [[Unigate]] and then [[Uniq plc|Uniq]].<ref name=\"hb2008\">{{cite web|url=http://www.wincanton.co.uk/about-us/the-wincanton-journey/|title=Wincaton Journey|last=|first=|date=|website=|publisher=Wincanton Plc|access-date=|accessdate=2016-08-02}}</ref>\n\nIn the 1970's, Wincanton diversified into new market sectors including [[petroleum]] and developed temperature controlled operations for the [[transport]]ation of [[food]] stuffs and refrigerated goods.<ref name=\"wincanton.co.uk\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.wincanton.co.uk/about-us/the-wincanton-journey/|title=Wincanton {{!}} 1925 to today, follow Wincanton's history|website=www.wincanton.co.uk|access-date=2016-08-02}}</ref> In the 1990's, Wincanton merged with [[Uniq plc|Unigate]] Chilled Distribution, and entered the [[Retail|retail market]], through the acquisition of Glass Glover in February 1993.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.heraldscotland.com/news/12619743.Unigate_buys_Glass_Glover/|title=Unigate buys Glass Glover|date=16 February 1993|publisher=Herald Scotland|accessdate=22 June 2018}}</ref> In March 2001, Wincanton plc [[Demerger|demerged]] from Uniq, and was listed on the [[London Stock Exchange]].<ref name=\"wincanton.co.uk\"/>\n\nIn November 2015, Wincanton sold its [[records management]] business (WRM) to [[Restore plc|Restore]] for approximately \u00a355.7m to reduce its average net [[Debt|indebtedness]], and allow room for growth.<ref name=\"Reports and presentations\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.wincanton.co.uk/investors/reports-and-presentations/|title=Reports and presentations|website=www.wincanton.co.uk|access-date=2016-08-02}}</ref> In February 2016, Wincanton partnered with [[Magnet Kitchens]] to produce forty four new double decker [[Articulated trailer bus|articulated trailers]] which was an investment of \u00a32 million.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.wincanton.co.uk/media-centre/press-releases/wincanton-helps-magnet-cut-carbon-emissions/|title=Partnership pioneers unique double decker articulated trailers|website=www.wincanton.co.uk|access-date=2016-08-02}}</ref> \n\nIn March 2016, Wincanton launched EnergyLink, a network based in the United Kingdom to support greater flexibility in delivery services for the [[Energy industry|energy sector]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.wincanton.co.uk/media-centre/press-releases/wincanton-launches-new-energy-sector-services/|title=Wincanton launches new energy sector services|website=www.wincanton.co.uk|access-date=2016-08-02}}</ref> \n\nIn April 2016, Wincanton gained further growth of its operations at the [[Port of Southampton]] after moving to a new base and investing in new equipment, supported by extra [[Rail transport|rail]] capacity. <ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.wincanton.co.uk/media-centre/press-releases/wincanton-grows-at-port-of-southampton/|title=Wincanton logistics expands at Port of Southampton|website=www.wincanton.co.uk|access-date=2016-08-02}}</ref> In June 2016, Wincanton renewed its distribution deal with [[Sainsbury's|J Sainsburys PLC]] for an additional five years. The business has been a customer of Wincanton for the past twenty one years.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.londonstockexchange.com/exchange/news/market-news/market-news-detail/WIN/12854115.html|title=Contract Renewal with Sainsbury's - RNS - London Stock Exchange|website=www.londonstockexchange.com|access-date=2016-08-02}}</ref>\n\nIn July 2016, Wincanton renewed a contract with [[The Co-operative Group]] for a further five years, which brings the contract to twenty five years. As part of the agreement, around seven hundred staff of Wincanton and a fleet of more than five hundred vehicles will support the Co Op, by making around 130k journeys each year to as many as 1,000 stores of the Co-op across the United Kingdom.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://bdaily.co.uk/industrials/26-07-2016/the-co-op-signs-five-year-logistics-deal-with-wincanton-plc/|title=The Co-op signs five-year logistics deal with Wincanton plc|last=Bell|first=Richard|access-date=2016-08-02}}</ref> \n\nIn October 2019, Wincanton plc expressed an interest in merging with [[Eddie Stobart Logistics|Eddie Stobart]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www-cityam-com.cdn.ampproject.org/v/s/www.cityam.com/wincanton-pursues-possible-merger-with-eddie-stobart/amp/?amp_js_v=a2&amp_gsa=1&usqp=mq331AQCKAE%3D#aoh=15734962302273&referrer=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.google.com&amp_tf=From%20%251%24s&ampshare=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.cityam.com%2Fwincanton-pursues-possible-merger-with-eddie-stobart%2F|title=Wincanton pursues possible merger with Eddie Stobart|date=18 October 2019|publisher=City AM|accessdate=11 November 2019}}</ref> Wincanton, later withdrew their offer, saying that it had \u201cyet to receive full disclosure of the information requested to enable it to complete its due diligence exercise\u201d.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.logisticsmanager.com/wincanton-withdraws-eddie-stobart-interest/|title= Wincanton withdraws Eddie Stobart interest|publisher=Logistics Manager|date=25 November 2019|accessdate=25 November 2019}}</ref>\n\n== Headquarters ==\nThe company's origins are in [[Wincanton]], [[Somerset]], although the head office is now based in Methuen Park, [[Chippenham]], [[Wiltshire]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.google.co.uk/maps/place/Wincanton/@51.4945473,-1.60133,10z/data=!4m8!1m2!2m1!1swincanton+plc!3m4!1s0x0:0x7561bd1a219b0763!8m2!3d51.445823!4d-2.1469688|title=Google Maps|website=Google Maps|access-date=2016-08-02}}</ref>\n\n==Operations==\nWincanton currently directly employs in the region of 20,000 people across the United Kingdom and Ireland through a network of over two hundred sites.<ref name=\"ReferenceA\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.wincanton.co.uk/about-us/wincanton-overview/|title=Wincanton {{!}} transport, storage, supply chain innovation|website=www.wincanton.co.uk|access-date=2016-08-02}}</ref> As of 2016, the Wincanton fleet comprises over 3,400 [[vehicle]]s including conventional [[truck]]s and trailers, as well as a range of specialist equipment including skeletal trailers, tankers and [[Heavy equipment|construction vehicles]].<ref name=\"ReferenceA\"/>\n\n== Services ==\nWincanton offers road transport and [[Distribution (business)|distribution]], container [[logistics]], specialist transport to [[Construction|construction sites]], tankers for all liquid and powder products, including [[Lubricant|petroleum and lubricants]], [[Delivery (commerce)|home delivery]] and [[fleet management]] and vehicle maintenance through its subsidiary business, Pullman Fleet Services.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.wincanton.co.uk/services/transport/|title=Transport and Logistics Management - Transport Companies UK|website=www.wincanton.co.uk|access-date=2016-08-02}}</ref> Wincanton offers dedicated and shared user warehousing, [[Bonded warehouse|bonded warehousing]] and other services. \n\nThese include co packing, [[automation]], eFulfilment, off quay [[solution]]s, returns management, [[recycling]] and [[Packaging and labeling|packaging]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.wincanton.co.uk/services/warehouse-solutions/|title=Warehousing logistics and services from Wincanton|website=www.wincanton.co.uk|access-date=2016-08-02}}</ref> Wincanton also offers integrated [[IT service management|IT services]], change management and people transition ([[Transfer of Undertakings (Protection of Employment) Regulations 2006|TUPE]]) services.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.wincanton.co.uk/services/value-added-services/|title=Value Added Services - Value Chain at Wincanton|website=www.wincanton.co.uk|access-date=2016-08-02}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Wincanton Plc}}\n[[Category:Companies based in Wiltshire]]\n[[Category:Logistics companies of the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:Transport operators of the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:Business services companies established in 1925]]\n[[Category:1925 establishments in England]]\n", "name_user": "Alistair1978", "label": "safe", "comment": "typos (viaWP:JWB)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wincanton_plc"}
{"title_page": "98th Battalion (Lincoln & Welland), CEF", "text_new": "[[File:Canadian Red Ensign 1868-1921.svg|thumb|right|150px]]98th Battalion (Lincoln & Welland), CEF, was an infantry battalion of the [[World War I|Great War]] [[Canadian Expeditionary Force]]. The 98th Battalion was authorized on 22 December 1915 and embarked for Britain on 16 July 1916, where the battalion provided reinforcements to the Canadian Corps in the field until 6 October 1916, when its personnel were absorbed by the 12th Reserve Battalion, CEF. The battalion disbanded on 17 July 1917.25<ref>Canadian Forces Publication A-DH-267-003 Insignia and Lineages of the Canadian Forces. Volume 3: Combat Arms Regiments.</ref>\n\nThe 98th Battalion recruited in Lincoln and Welland Counties and was mobilized at Welland, Ontario.<ref>Meek, John F. ''Over the Top! The Canadian Infantry in the First World War.'' Orangeville, Ont.: The Author, 1971. {{ISBN|0906158109}}</ref>\n\nThe 98th Battalion was commanded by Lt.-Col. H.A. Rose from 8 July 1916 to 6 October 1916.<ref>Meek, John F. ''Over the Top! The Canadian Infantry in the First World War.'' Orangeville, Ont.: The Author, 1971. {{ISBN|0906158109}}</ref>\n\nThe 98th Battalion was awarded the battle honour THE GREAT WAR 1916.<ref>Meek, John F. ''Over the Top! The Canadian Infantry in the First World War.'' Orangeville, Ont.: The Author, 1971. {{ISBN|0906158109}}</ref>\n\nThe 98th Battalion (Lincoln & Welland), CEF, is perpetuated by [[The Lincoln and Welland Regiment]].<ref>Canadian Forces Publication A-DH-267-003 Insignia and Lineages of the Canadian Forces. Volume 3: Combat Arms Regiments.</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==Sources==\nCanadian Expeditionary Force 1914\u20131919 by Col. G.W.L. Nicholson, CD, Queen's Printer, Ottawa, Ontario, 1962\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:98th Battalion (Lincoln and Welland), CEF}}\n[[Category:Military history of Canada]]\n[[Category:Battalions of the Canadian Expeditionary Force|098]]\n[[Category:Military history of Ontario]]\n", "text_old": "[[File:Canadian Red Ensign 1868-1921.svg|thumb|right|150px]]98th Battalion (Lincoln & Welland), CEF, was an infantry battalion of the [[World War I|Great War]] [[Canadian Expeditionary Force]]. The 98th Battalion was authorized on 22 December 1915 and embarked for Britain on 16 July 1916, where the battalion provided reinforcements to the Canadian Corps in the field until 6 October 1916, when its personnel were absorbed by the 12th Reserve Battalion, CEF. The battalion disbanded on 17 July 1917.25<ref>Canadian Forces Publication A-DH-267-003 Insignia and Lineages of the Canadian Forces. Volume 3: Combat Arms Regiments.</ref>\n\nThe 98th Battalion recruited in Lincoln and Welland Counties and was mobilized at Welland, Ontario.<ref>Meek, John F. ''Over the Top! The Canadian Infantry in the First World War.'' Orangeville, Ont.: The Author, 1971. {{ISBN|0906158109}}</ref>\n\nThe 98th Battalion was commanded by Lt.-Col. H.A. Rose from 8 July 1916 to 6 October 1916.<ref>Meek, John F. ''Over the Top! The Canadian Infantry in the First World War.'' Orangeville, Ont.: The Author, 1971. {{ISBN|0906158109}}</ref>\n\nThe 98th Battalion was awarded the battle honour THE GREAT WAR 1916.<ref>Meek, John F. ''Over the Top! The Canadian Infantry in the First World War.'' Orangeville, Ont.: The Author, 1971. {{ISBN|0906158109}}</ref>\n\nThe 98th Battalion (Lincoln & Welland), CEF, is perpetuated by [[The Lincoln and Welland Regiment]].<ref>Canadian Forces Publication A-DH-267-003 Insignia and Lineages of the Canadian Forces. Volume 3: Combat Arms Regiments.</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==Sources==\nCanadian Expeditionary Force 1914\u20131919 by Col. G.W.L. Nicholson, CD, Queen's Printer, Ottawa, Ontario, 1962\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:98th Battalion (Lincoln and Welland), CEF}}\n[[Category:Military history of Canada]]\n[[Category:Battalions of the Canadian Expeditionary Force|084]]\n[[Category:Military history of Ontario]]\n", "name_user": "Nthep", "label": "safe", "comment": "fix catsort", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/98th_Battalion_(Lincoln_%26_Welland),_CEF"}
{"title_page": "Absa Bank Ghana Limited", "text_new": "{{short description|Ghanaian commercial bank}}\n\n{{EngvarB|date=March 2020}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=March 2020}}\n{{Infobox company \n| name = Absa Bank Ghana Limited\n| type = [[Subsidiary]] of [[Absa Group Limited]]\n| traded_as = \n| industry = [[Financial services]]\n| logo = [[File:ABSA Group Limited Logo.svg|120px]]\n| foundation ={{Start date and years ago|1917}}\n| location= Absa House, J.E. Atta-Mills High Street, [[Accra]], [[Ghana]]\n| revenue =\n| key_people = '''Charles Alexander Cofie'''<br/>[[Chairman]]<ref name=\"1R\">{{cite web|title=Ghana: Absa Group's Income Hits U.S.$2.3 Billion |newspaper=[[Ghanaian Times]] via [[AllAfrica.com]] |date=8 August 2018 |access-date=26 March 2020 | url=https://allafrica.com/stories/201808080785.html | author=Ghanaian Times |location=Accra}}</ref><br>'''Abena Osei-Poku'''<br/>[[Managing Director]] and [[CEO]]<ref name=\"2R\">{{cite web|publisher=The Finder Online |date=20 March 2020 |  url=https://thefinderonline.com/news/item/18903-absa-bank-ghana-committed-to-women-economic-empowerment |title=\u2018Absa Bank Ghana committed to women economic empowerment\u2019 |author=The Finder Online |place=Accra |access-date=26 March 2020}}</ref>\n| num_employees = \n| net_income      = \n| net_income_year = \n| assets          = GHS:8.994 billion (US$1,578 billion) (2018)\n| products        = Loans, checking, savings, mortgages, debit and credit cards, wealth management, investments, etc.\n| homepage        = {{url|https://www.absa.com.gh/}}\n}}\n\n'''Absa Bank Ghana Limited''' (ABGL), formerly known as '''Barclays Bank Ghana Limited''', is a commercial bank in [[Ghana]], licenced by the [[Bank of Ghana]], the country's central bank and national banking regulator.<ref name=\"3R\">{{cite web|url=https://www.bog.gov.gh/supervision-regulation/registered-institutions/banks/ |title=List of Registered Commercial Banks in Ghana |date=March 2020 |publisher=[[Bank of Ghana]] |place=Accra |access-date=26 March 2020 |author=[[Bank of Ghana]]}}</ref> ABGL is a subsidiary of [[Absa Group Limited]], a financial services [[Conglomerate (company)|conglomerate]], headquartered in [[South Africa]], with subsidiaries in 12 [[Africa]]n countries and with assets in excess of US$87 billion as of 30 June 2017,<ref name=\"4R\">{{cite web|url=https://www.relbanks.com/africa/south-africa/barclays-africa |title=Profile of Barclays Africa Group (now Absa Group Limited) |publisher=Relbanks.com |date=July 2017 | author=Relbanks.com |access-date=26 March 2020}}</ref> ABGL's shares of [[stock]] trade on the [[Johannesburg Stock Exchange]] under the symbol '''ABG'''.<ref name=\"5R\">{{cite web| url=https://www.moneyweb.co.za/tools-and-data/click-a-company/ABG/ |title=Financial overview of the JSE listed company Absa Group Ltd. (ABG) |publisher=Moneyweb South Africa |date=25 March 2020 |author=Moneyweb |access-date=26 March 2020 | location=Johannesburg}}</ref>\n\n==Location==\nThe headquarters of the bank are located at Absa House, J.E. Atta-Mills High Street, in the [[central business district]] of [[Accra]], the capital of Ghana.<ref name=\"3R\"/> The geographical coordinates of the bank's headquarters are:05\u00b032'29.0\"N,  0\u00b012'25.0\"W (Latitude:5.541389; Longitude:-0.206944).<ref name=\"6R\">{{google maps|access-date=26 March 2020 | url=https://www.google.com/maps/place/5%C2%B032'29.0%22N+0%C2%B012'25.0%22W/@5.5412663,-0.2068771,82m/data=!3m1!1e3!4m5!3m4!1s0x0:0x0!8m2!3d5.5413889!4d-0.2069444 |title=Location of the Headquarters of Absa Bank Ghana Limited}}</ref>\n\n==Overview==\nAbsa Bank Ghana is a large financial services company, serving corporate clients, high networth individuals, retail customers and [[small and medium enterprise]]s. As of 31 December 2018, the bank had assets of GHS:8,994,562,000 (US$1.578  billion), with shareholders' equity of GHS:1,337,473,000 (US$235 million).<ref name=\"7R\">{{cite web|publisher=Absa Bank Ghana Limited | title=Barclays Bank Ghana Limited: Audited Condensed Financial Statements as of 31 December 2018 |date=31 December 2018 | author=Absa Bank Ghana Limited |access-date=26 March 2020 |\nurl=https://www.absa.com.gh/content/dam/ghana/absa/pdf/annual-reports/financial-statement-2018.pdf |location=Accra}}</ref>\n\n==History==\nAccording to the archives of Barclays Bank Ghana, ''Colonial Bank'' opened shop in what was then known as the [[Gold Coast (British colony)|Gold Coast]] in 1917. In 1925, [[Anglo-Egyptian Bank]], [[Colonial Bank (West Indies)|Colonial Bank]] and [[National Bank of South Africa]] were merged to form [[Barclays Bank (Dominion, Colonial and Overseas)]]. In 1975, the [[government of Ghana]] acquired 40 percent shareholding in Barclays Bank of Ghana. That stake was returned in 2003. In 2013, the bank became a member of [[Barclays Africa Group]], with Barclays Plc holding a controlling 62.3 percent majority ownership.<ref name=\"8R\">{{cite web| url=https://www.archive.barclays.com/items/show/170 |title=History of Barclays Bank Ghana Limited |date=2020 | publisher=Barclays Bank Archives |access-date=26 March 2020 | place=London | author=Barclays Plc}}</ref>\n\n==Name change==\nIn 2016, Barclays Bank Plc, which owned 62.3 percent of [[Barclays Africa Group]] (BAG), the then majority shareholder of Barclays Bank of Ghana Limited, decided to divest its majority shareholding in BAG, worth \u20a43.5 billion at that time. In 2017 Barclays reduced its shareholding in BAG to 14.9 percent.<ref name=\"9R\">{{cite web|date=26 February 2016 |access-date=26 March 2020 |url=https://www.ft.com/content/01d64502-dca4-11e5-827d-4dfbe0213e07 |title=Barclays set to exit African business |\nnewspaper=[[The Financial Times]] |author=Martin Arnold and Patrick Jenkins |location=London}}</ref>\n\nFollowing that, in 2018 BAG re-branded to Absa Group Limited.\nUnder the terms of that re-brand, Absa had until June 2020 to change the names of its subsidiaries in 12 African countries.<ref name=\"10R\">{{cite web|newspaper=[[Business Daily Africa]] | url=https://www.businessdailyafrica.com/corporate/companies/Barclays-Africa-officially-rebrands-to-Absa/4003102-4657806-c99e5u/index.html |title=Barclays Africa returns to its SA roots with rebrand |date=11 July 2018 |access-date=26 March 2020 | author=Reuters}}</ref>\n\nIn Ghana, the re-brand concluded on 10 February 2020, when both the bank's legal and business names became Absa Bank Ghana Limited.<ref name=\"11R\">{{cite web| url=https://www.pulse.com.gh/bi/finance/barclays-bank-ghana-officially-moves-to-become-absa-bank-ghana-limited/e0w5qn1 | title=Barclays Bank Ghana officially moves to become Absa Bank Ghana Limited |publisher=Pulse.com |author=Berlinda Entsie | date=10 February 2020 |access-date=26 March 2020 |place=Accra}}</ref>\n\n==Governance==\nThe bank is supervised by a [[board of directors]], chaired by Charles A. Cofie, one of the non-executive directors.<ref name=\"1R\"/> The managing director and CEO is Abena Osei-Poku.<ref name=\"2R\"/>\n\n==See also==\n*[[List of banks in Ghana]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [https://www.absa.com.gh/personal/  Company Website]\n\n{{coord|05|32|29|N|00|12|25|W|display=title}}\n\n[[Category:Companies of Ghana]]\n[[Category:Absa Group Limited]]\n[[Category:Banks established in 1917]]\n[[Category:1917 establishments in the British Empire]]\n[[Category:1917 establishments in Gold Coast (British colony)]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Ghanaian commercial bank}}\n\n{{EngvarB|date=March 2020}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=March 2020}}\n{{Infobox company \n| name = Absa Bank Ghana Limited\n| type = [[Subsidiary]] of [[Absa Group Limited]]\n| traded_as = \n| industry = [[Financial services]]\n| logo = [[File:ABSA Group Limited Logo.svg|120px]]\n| foundation ={{Start date and years ago|1917}}\n| location= Absa House, J.E. Atta-Mills High Street, [[Accra]], [[Ghana]]\n| revenue =\n| key_people = '''Charles Alexander Cofie'''<br/>[[Chairman]]<ref name=\"1R\">{{cite web|title=Ghana: Absa Group's Income Hits U.S.$2.3 Billion |newspaper=[[Ghanaian Times]] via [[AllAfrica.com]] |date=8 August 2018 |access-date=26 March 2020 | url=https://allafrica.com/stories/201808080785.html | author=Ghanaian Times |location=Accra}}</ref><br>'''Abena Osei-Poku'''<br/>[[Managing Director]] and [[CEO]]<ref name=\"2R\">{{cite web|publisher=The Finder Online |date=20 March 2020 |  url=https://thefinderonline.com/news/item/18903-absa-bank-ghana-committed-to-women-economic-empowerment |title=\u2018Absa Bank Ghana committed to women economic empowerment\u2019 |author=The Finder Online |place=Accra |access-date=26 March 2020}}</ref>\n| num_employees = \n| net_income      = \n| net_income_year = \n| assets          = GHS:8.994 billion (US$1,578 billion) (2018)\n| products        = Loans, checking, savings, mortgages, debit and credit cards, wealth management, investments, etc.\n| homepage        = {{url|https://www.absa.com.gh/}}\n}}\n\n'''Absa Bank Ghana Limited''' (ABGL), formerly known as '''Barclays Bank Ghana Limited''', is a commercial bank in [[Ghana]], licenced by the [[Bank of Ghana]], the country's central bank and national banking regulator.<ref name=\"3R\">{{cite web|url=https://www.bog.gov.gh/supervision-regulation/registered-institutions/banks/ |title=List of Registered Commercial Banks in Ghana |date=March 2020 |publisher=[[Bank of Ghana]] |place=Accra |access-date=26 March 2020 |author=[[Bank of Ghana]]}}</ref> ABGL is a subsidiary of [[Absa Group Limited]], a financial services [[Conglomerate (company)|conglomerate]], headquartered in [[South Africa]], with subsidiaries in 12 [[Africa]]n countries and with assets in excess of US$87 billion as of 30 June 2017,<ref name=\"4R\">{{cite web|url=https://www.relbanks.com/africa/south-africa/barclays-africa |title=Profile of Barclays Africa Group (now Absa Group Limited) |publisher=Relbanks.com |date=July 2017 | author=Relbanks.com |access-date=26 March 2020}}</ref> ABGL's shares of [[stock]] trade on the [[Johannesburg Stock Exchange]] under the symbol '''ABG'''.<ref name=\"5R\">{{cite web| url=https://www.moneyweb.co.za/tools-and-data/click-a-company/ABG/ |title=Financial overview of the JSE listed company Absa Group Ltd. (ABG) |publisher=Moneyweb South Africa |date=25 March 2020 |author=Moneyweb |access-date=26 March 2020 | location=Johannesburg}}</ref>\n\n==Location==\nThe headquarters of the bank are located at Absa House, J.E. Atta-Mills High Street, in the [[central business district]] of [[Accra]], the capital of Ghana.<ref name=\"3R\"/> The geographical coordinates of the bank's headquarters are:05\u00b032'29.0\"N,  0\u00b012'25.0\"W (Latitude:5.541389; Longitude:-0.206944).<ref name=\"6R\">{{google maps|access-date=26 March 2020 | url=https://www.google.com/maps/place/5%C2%B032'29.0%22N+0%C2%B012'25.0%22W/@5.5412663,-0.2068771,82m/data=!3m1!1e3!4m5!3m4!1s0x0:0x0!8m2!3d5.5413889!4d-0.2069444 |title=Location of the Headquarters of Absa Bank Ghana Limited}}</ref>\n\n==Overview==\nAbsa Bank Ghana is a large financial services company, serving corporate clients, high networth individuals, retail customers and [[small and medium enterprise]]s. As of 31 December 2018, the bank had assets of GHS:8,994,562,000 (US$1.578  billion), with shareholders' equity of GHS:1,337,473,000 (US$235 million).<ref name=\"7R\">{{cite web|publisher=Absa Bank Ghana Limited | title=Barclays Bank Ghana Limited: Audited Condensed Financial Statements as of 31 December 2018 |date=31 December 2018 | author=Absa Bank Ghana Limited |access-date=26 March 2020 |\nurl=https://www.absa.com.gh/content/dam/ghana/absa/pdf/annual-reports/financial-statement-2018.pdf |location=Accra}}</ref>\n\n==History==\nAccording to the archives of Barclays Bank Ghana, ''Colonial Bank'' opened shop in what was then known as the [[Gold Coast]] in 1917. In 1925, [[Anglo-Egyptian Bank]], [[Colonial Bank (West Indies)|Colonial Bank]] and [[National Bank of South Africa]] were merged to form [[Barclays Bank (Dominion, Colonial and Overseas)]]. In 1975, the [[government of Ghana]] acquired 40 percent shareholding in Barclays Bank of Ghana. That stake was returned in 2003. In 2013, the bank became a member of [[Barclays Africa Group]], with Barclays Plc holding a controlling 62.3 percent majority ownership.<ref name=\"8R\">{{cite web| url=https://www.archive.barclays.com/items/show/170 |title=History of Barclays Bank Ghana Limited |date=2020 | publisher=Barclays Bank Archives |access-date=26 March 2020 | place=London | author=Barclays Plc}}</ref>\n\n==Name change==\nIn 2016, Barclays Bank Plc, which owned 62.3 percent of [[Barclays Africa Group]] (BAG), the then majority shareholder of Barclays Bank of Ghana Limited, decided to divest its majority shareholding in BAG, worth \u20a43.5 billion at that time. In 2017 Barclays reduced its shareholding in BAG to 14.9 percent.<ref name=\"9R\">{{cite web|date=26 February 2016 |access-date=26 March 2020 |url=https://www.ft.com/content/01d64502-dca4-11e5-827d-4dfbe0213e07 |title=Barclays set to exit African business |\nnewspaper=[[The Financial Times]] |author=Martin Arnold and Patrick Jenkins |location=London}}</ref>\n\nFollowing that, in 2018 BAG re-branded to Absa Group Limited.\nUnder the terms of that re-brand, Absa had until June 2020 to change the names of its subsidiaries in 12 African countries.<ref name=\"10R\">{{cite web|newspaper=[[Business Daily Africa]] | url=https://www.businessdailyafrica.com/corporate/companies/Barclays-Africa-officially-rebrands-to-Absa/4003102-4657806-c99e5u/index.html |title=Barclays Africa returns to its SA roots with rebrand |date=11 July 2018 |access-date=26 March 2020 | author=Reuters}}</ref>\n\nIn Ghana, the re-brand concluded on 10 February 2020, when both the bank's legal and business names became Absa Bank Ghana Limited.<ref name=\"11R\">{{cite web| url=https://www.pulse.com.gh/bi/finance/barclays-bank-ghana-officially-moves-to-become-absa-bank-ghana-limited/e0w5qn1 | title=Barclays Bank Ghana officially moves to become Absa Bank Ghana Limited |publisher=Pulse.com |author=Berlinda Entsie | date=10 February 2020 |access-date=26 March 2020 |place=Accra}}</ref>\n\n==Governance==\nThe bank is supervised by a [[board of directors]], chaired by Charles A. Cofie, one of the non-executive directors.<ref name=\"1R\"/> The managing director and CEO is Abena Osei-Poku.<ref name=\"2R\"/>\n\n==See also==\n*[[List of banks in Ghana]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [https://www.absa.com.gh/personal/  Company Website]\n\n{{coord|05|32|29|N|00|12|25|W|display=title}}\n\n[[Category:Companies of Ghana]]\n[[Category:Absa Group Limited]]\n[[Category:Banks established in 1917]]\n[[Category:1917 establishments in the British Empire]]\n[[Category:1917 establishments in Gold Coast (British colony)]]\n", "name_user": "Rodw", "label": "safe", "comment": "Disambiguating links toGold Coast(link changed toGold Coast (British colony)) usingDisamAssist.", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Absa_Bank_Ghana_Limited"}
{"title_page": "G. S. Lassey", "text_new": "{{short description|Ghanaian judge and author}}\n{{Infobox Judge\n| honorific-prefix =Justice\n| name =George Sewavi Lassey\n| honorific-suffix =\n| image =\n| imagesize =\n| caption =\n| office = Appeal Court Judge\n| term_start = 1967\n| term_end = 1980s\n| nominator =<!-- Can be repeated up to eight times by changing the number -->\n| appointer = [[Joseph Arthur Ankrah]]\n| predecessor =\n| successor =<!-- Can be repeated up to eight times by changing the number -->\n| office1 = [[Supreme Court of Ghana|Supreme Court Judge]]\n| nominator1 = [[Kwame Nkrumah]]\n| term_start1 = 1965\n| term_end1 = 1966\n| predecessor1 = [[Charles Sterling Acolatse]]\n| successor1 = \n| office2 = High Court Judge\n| president2 = [[Kwame Nkrumah]]\n| term_start2 = 1 September 1962\n| term_end2 = 1964\n| predecessor2 =\n| successor2 =\n| birth_date = \n| birth_place =[[Gold Coast (British colony)|Gold Coast]]\n| death_date =\n| death_place =\n| nationality =[[Ghana]]ian\n| spouse =\n| party =\n| relations =\n| children =\n| residence =\n| alma_mater ={{unbulleted|[[Achimota School]]|[[University of London]]}}\n| occupation =\n| profession =\n| signature =\n| website =\n| footnotes =\n}}\n\n'''George Sewavi Lassey''' was a [[Ghanaian]] [[judge]]. He served as a High Court Judge from 1962 to 1965, a [[Supreme Court Judge]] from 1965 to 1966 and an Appeals Court Judge from 1966 until his retirement.\n\n==Early life and education==\nLassey was born in [[Keta]], a town in the [[Volta Region]] of [[Ghana]] to Moses Adjevi Lassey, a merchant of Keta.<ref name=\"LARBI\">{{cite journal |title=West Africa, Issues 4224-4241 |url=https://books.google.com.gh/books?id=59gVAQAAIAAJ&q=George+Sewavi+Lassey&dq=George+Sewavi+Lassey&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwix-Jm9hP7nAhVS5eAKHQnTB_8Q6AEILTAD |publisher=West Africa Publishing Company Limited |page=46 |date=2000}}</ref> He had his secondary education at [[Achimota School]] where he studied under the tutelage of [[William Ofori Atta]] (who later became a member of [[The Big Six (Ghana)|The Big Six]]).<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.graphic.com.gh/features/features/remembering-william-ofori-atta-a-model-of-peace-unity-and-reconciliation.html |title=Remembering William Ofori Atta - A model of peace, unity and reconciliation |publisher=Graphic Online |accessdate=3 March 2020}}</ref> He had his tertiary education at the [[University of London]] where he obtained his [[bachelor of laws]] degree (llb).<ref>{{cite journal |title=Graya:\u00a0A Magazine for Members of Gray's Inn, Volume 7 |url=https://books.google.com.gh/books?id=uOMyAAAAIAAJ&dq=george+sewavi+lassey&focus=searchwithinvolume&q=Sewavi |publisher=Gray's Inn |page=139 |date=1949 |journal=Graya:\u00a0A Magazine for Members of Gray's Inn}}</ref> He was called to the bar at [[Grays Inn]].<ref name=\"LARBI\"/>\n\n==Career==\nPrior to his appointment to the Supreme Court bench, he was a High Court judge stationed at [[Cape Coast]]. He served on the High Court bench from 1 September 1962<ref>{{cite book |last=Amissah |first=A. N. E |date=1981 |title=The contribution of the courts to government:\u00a0a West African view |url=https://books.google.com.gh/books?id=3DeOAAAAMAAJ&q=G.+S.+Lassey&dq=G.+S.+Lassey&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwjc59r9gP7nAhUeA2MBHZv7DK8Q6AEIITAB |publisher=Clarendon Press |page=179}}</ref><ref>{{cite book |author=Ghana |date=1976 |title=The Supreme Court of Ghana centenary : souvenir, 1876-1976 |url=https://books.google.com.gh/books?id=cQFQAQAAMAAJ&q=G.+S.+Lassey&dq=G.+S.+Lassey&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwjc59r9gP7nAhUeA2MBHZv7DK8Q6AEIKDAC |publisher=University Press |page=33}}</ref> until 1965 when he was appointed to the Supreme Court bench<ref>{{cite journal |title=West African directory |publisher=T. Skinner, London |url=https://books.google.com.gh/books?id=n0vjAAAAMAAJ&dq=g+s+lassey+supreme+court&focus=searchwithinvolume&q=g+s+lassey |page=79 |date=1966}}</ref> to replace Justice [[Charles Sterling Acolatse]] who was due for retirement. In 1966, following the overthrow of [[Kwame Nkrumah]] by the [[National Liberation Council]], the Supreme Court was replaced by the Appeals Court and Justice Lassey served as an Appeals Court Judge from 1966 until his retirement in the 1980s.<ref>{{cite journal |title=West Africa Annual, Issue 8 |url=https://books.google.com.gh/books?id=SwbBjKf-k2UC&q=george+sewavi+lassey&dq=george+sewavi+lassey&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwj_svD618nlAhVx8eAKHTKhBVEQ6AEIJzAC |author=James Clarke |page=84 |year=1967 |publisher=West Africa Annual}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal |title=Ghana Year Book 1967 |url=https://books.google.com.gh/books?id=KDAuAQAAIAAJ&q=george+sewavi+lassey&dq=george+sewavi+lassey&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwj_svD618nlAhVx8eAKHTKhBVEQ6AEIODAF |publisher=Graphic Corporation |page=29 |year=1968 |journal=Ghana Year Book}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal |title=The Supreme Court of Ghana Law Reports, Volume 1 |url=https://books.google.com.gh/books?id=gP9QAQAAMAAJ&q=G.+S.+Lassey&dq=G.+S.+Lassey&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwjc59r9gP7nAhUeA2MBHZv7DK8Q6AEISzAI |page=vii |date=1978 |publisher=Ghana Law Reporting |journal=The Supreme Court of Ghana Law Reports}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal |title=The United Kingdom, the Commonwealth of Nations, a Directory of Governments, Volume 1 |url=https://books.google.com.gh/books?id=BSYkAQAAIAAJ&q=G.+S.+Lassey&dq=G.+S.+Lassey&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwjc59r9gP7nAhUeA2MBHZv7DK8Q6AEIUTAJ |publisher=Political Research, Dallas, Texas |page=284 |date=1979}}</ref><ref>{{cite book |last=Essilfie-Condua |first=Nana\n|title=Ghana:\u00a0The 3rd Republic |date=1991 |page=86 |url=https://books.google.com.gh/books?id=M70MAAAAYAAJ&dq=g+s+lassey+supreme+court&focus=searchwithinvolume&q=g+s+lassey |publisher=Nefisco Publications}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n*[[List of judges of the Supreme Court of Ghana]]\n*[[Supreme Court of Ghana]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Lassey, George Sewavi}}\n[[Category:Justices of the Supreme Court of Ghana]]\n[[Category:Date of birth unknown]]\n[[Category:Alumni of Achimota School]]\n[[Category:Alumni of the University of London]]\n[[Category:Ghanaian judges]]\n[[Category:Date of death unknown]]\n\n\n{{Ghana-bio-stub}}\n{{Africa-law-bio-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Ghanaian judge and author}}\n{{Infobox Judge\n| honorific-prefix =Justice\n| name =George Sewavi Lassey\n| honorific-suffix =\n| image =\n| imagesize =\n| caption =\n| office = Appeal Court Judge\n| term_start = 1967\n| term_end = 1980s\n| nominator =<!-- Can be repeated up to eight times by changing the number -->\n| appointer = [[Joseph Arthur Ankrah]]\n| predecessor =\n| successor =<!-- Can be repeated up to eight times by changing the number -->\n| office1 = [[Supreme Court of Ghana|Supreme Court Judge]]\n| nominator1 = [[Kwame Nkrumah]]\n| term_start1 = 1965\n| term_end1 = 1966\n| predecessor1 = [[Charles Sterling Acolatse]]\n| successor1 = \n| office2 = High Court Judge\n| president2 = [[Kwame Nkrumah]]\n| term_start2 = 1 September 1962\n| term_end2 = 1964\n| predecessor2 =\n| successor2 =\n| birth_date = \n| birth_place =[[Gold Coast]]\n| death_date =\n| death_place =\n| nationality =[[Ghana]]ian\n| spouse =\n| party =\n| relations =\n| children =\n| residence =\n| alma_mater ={{unbulleted|[[Achimota School]]|[[University of London]]}}\n| occupation =\n| profession =\n| signature =\n| website =\n| footnotes =\n}}\n\n'''George Sewavi Lassey''' was a [[Ghanaian]] [[judge]]. He served as a High Court Judge from 1962 to 1965, a [[Supreme Court Judge]] from 1965 to 1966 and an Appeals Court Judge from 1966 until his retirement.\n\n==Early life and education==\nLassey was born in [[Keta]], a town in the [[Volta Region]] of [[Ghana]] to Moses Adjevi Lassey, a merchant of Keta.<ref name=\"LARBI\">{{cite journal |title=West Africa, Issues 4224-4241 |url=https://books.google.com.gh/books?id=59gVAQAAIAAJ&q=George+Sewavi+Lassey&dq=George+Sewavi+Lassey&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwix-Jm9hP7nAhVS5eAKHQnTB_8Q6AEILTAD |publisher=West Africa Publishing Company Limited |page=46 |date=2000}}</ref> He had his secondary education at [[Achimota School]] where he studied under the tutelage of [[William Ofori Atta]] (who later became a member of [[The Big Six (Ghana)|The Big Six]]).<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.graphic.com.gh/features/features/remembering-william-ofori-atta-a-model-of-peace-unity-and-reconciliation.html |title=Remembering William Ofori Atta - A model of peace, unity and reconciliation |publisher=Graphic Online |accessdate=3 March 2020}}</ref> He had his tertiary education at the [[University of London]] where he obtained his [[bachelor of laws]] degree (llb).<ref>{{cite journal |title=Graya:\u00a0A Magazine for Members of Gray's Inn, Volume 7 |url=https://books.google.com.gh/books?id=uOMyAAAAIAAJ&dq=george+sewavi+lassey&focus=searchwithinvolume&q=Sewavi |publisher=Gray's Inn |page=139 |date=1949 |journal=Graya:\u00a0A Magazine for Members of Gray's Inn}}</ref> He was called to the bar at [[Grays Inn]].<ref name=\"LARBI\"/>\n\n==Career==\nPrior to his appointment to the Supreme Court bench, he was a High Court judge stationed at [[Cape Coast]]. He served on the High Court bench from 1 September 1962<ref>{{cite book |last=Amissah |first=A. N. E |date=1981 |title=The contribution of the courts to government:\u00a0a West African view |url=https://books.google.com.gh/books?id=3DeOAAAAMAAJ&q=G.+S.+Lassey&dq=G.+S.+Lassey&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwjc59r9gP7nAhUeA2MBHZv7DK8Q6AEIITAB |publisher=Clarendon Press |page=179}}</ref><ref>{{cite book |author=Ghana |date=1976 |title=The Supreme Court of Ghana centenary : souvenir, 1876-1976 |url=https://books.google.com.gh/books?id=cQFQAQAAMAAJ&q=G.+S.+Lassey&dq=G.+S.+Lassey&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwjc59r9gP7nAhUeA2MBHZv7DK8Q6AEIKDAC |publisher=University Press |page=33}}</ref> until 1965 when he was appointed to the Supreme Court bench<ref>{{cite journal |title=West African directory |publisher=T. Skinner, London |url=https://books.google.com.gh/books?id=n0vjAAAAMAAJ&dq=g+s+lassey+supreme+court&focus=searchwithinvolume&q=g+s+lassey |page=79 |date=1966}}</ref> to replace Justice [[Charles Sterling Acolatse]] who was due for retirement. In 1966, following the overthrow of [[Kwame Nkrumah]] by the [[National Liberation Council]], the Supreme Court was replaced by the Appeals Court and Justice Lassey served as an Appeals Court Judge from 1966 until his retirement in the 1980s.<ref>{{cite journal |title=West Africa Annual, Issue 8 |url=https://books.google.com.gh/books?id=SwbBjKf-k2UC&q=george+sewavi+lassey&dq=george+sewavi+lassey&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwj_svD618nlAhVx8eAKHTKhBVEQ6AEIJzAC |author=James Clarke |page=84 |year=1967 |publisher=West Africa Annual}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal |title=Ghana Year Book 1967 |url=https://books.google.com.gh/books?id=KDAuAQAAIAAJ&q=george+sewavi+lassey&dq=george+sewavi+lassey&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwj_svD618nlAhVx8eAKHTKhBVEQ6AEIODAF |publisher=Graphic Corporation |page=29 |year=1968 |journal=Ghana Year Book}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal |title=The Supreme Court of Ghana Law Reports, Volume 1 |url=https://books.google.com.gh/books?id=gP9QAQAAMAAJ&q=G.+S.+Lassey&dq=G.+S.+Lassey&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwjc59r9gP7nAhUeA2MBHZv7DK8Q6AEISzAI |page=vii |date=1978 |publisher=Ghana Law Reporting |journal=The Supreme Court of Ghana Law Reports}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal |title=The United Kingdom, the Commonwealth of Nations, a Directory of Governments, Volume 1 |url=https://books.google.com.gh/books?id=BSYkAQAAIAAJ&q=G.+S.+Lassey&dq=G.+S.+Lassey&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwjc59r9gP7nAhUeA2MBHZv7DK8Q6AEIUTAJ |publisher=Political Research, Dallas, Texas |page=284 |date=1979}}</ref><ref>{{cite book |last=Essilfie-Condua |first=Nana\n|title=Ghana:\u00a0The 3rd Republic |date=1991 |page=86 |url=https://books.google.com.gh/books?id=M70MAAAAYAAJ&dq=g+s+lassey+supreme+court&focus=searchwithinvolume&q=g+s+lassey |publisher=Nefisco Publications}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n*[[List of judges of the Supreme Court of Ghana]]\n*[[Supreme Court of Ghana]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Lassey, George Sewavi}}\n[[Category:Justices of the Supreme Court of Ghana]]\n[[Category:Date of birth unknown]]\n[[Category:Alumni of Achimota School]]\n[[Category:Alumni of the University of London]]\n[[Category:Ghanaian judges]]\n[[Category:Date of death unknown]]\n\n\n{{Ghana-bio-stub}}\n{{Africa-law-bio-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Rodw", "label": "safe", "comment": "Disambiguating links toGold Coast(link changed toGold Coast (British colony)) usingDisamAssist.", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/G._S._Lassey"}
{"title_page": "Tacumshane", "text_new": "{{morefootnotes|date=February 2020}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=February 2020}}\n{{Use Irish English|date=February 2020}}\n{{Infobox settlement\n|name                   = Tacumshane\n|other_name             = {{pad top italic|Teach Coimse\u00e1in}}\n|settlement_type        = Village\n|image_skyline          = Tacumshane Windmill (geograph 6275920).jpg\n|image_caption          = Tacumshane Windmill \n|pushpin_map            = Ireland\n|pushpin_label_position = right\n|pushpin_map_caption    = Location in Ireland\n|subdivision_type       = Country\n|subdivision_name       = [[Republic of Ireland|Ireland]]\n|subdivision_type1      = [[Provinces of Ireland|Province]]\n|subdivision_name1      = [[Leinster]]\n|subdivision_type3      = [[Counties of Ireland|County]]\n|subdivision_name3      = [[County Wexford]]\n|established_title      = \n|established_date       = \n|unit_pref              = Metric\n|area_footnotes         = \n|area_total_km2         = \n|population_as_of       = \n|population_footnotes   = \n|population_total       = \n|population_urban       = \n|population_density_km2 = auto\n|timezone1              = [[West European Time|WET]] \n|utc_offset1            = +0\n|timezone1_DST          = [[Irish Standard Time|IST]] ([[Western European Summer Time|WEST]]) \n|utc_offset1_DST        = -1\n|coordinates            = {{coord|52.207|-6.41|dim:100000_region:IE|format=dms|display=inline,title}}\n|elevation_footnotes    = \n|elevation_m            = 24\n|blank_name             = [[Irish grid reference system|Irish Grid Reference]]\n|blank_info             = {{iem4ibx|T072076}}\n|website                = \n|footnotes              = \n}}\n\n'''Tacumshane''' ({{Irish place name|Teach Coimse\u00e1in}}) is a small village in the southeast of [[County Wexford]], [[Republic of Ireland|Ireland]]. It is located 15&nbsp;km south of Wexford town.\n\n==Name==\nThe official name of the village is Tacumshane. In [[Irish language|Irish]] it is called ''Teach Coimse\u00e1in'' (House of Se\u00e1n). The name of the village is often misspelled as \"Tacumshin\" as opposed to \"Tacumshane\". The lake and [[townland]] is spelled \"Tacumshin\", while the village and parish are spelled \"Tacumshane\". \nAbout two miles away is the townsland of Churchtown which was once called Tacumshane. It is where Tacumshane castle stood until it was demolished in 1984 by a local farmer. The Fence is the townsland located in the village of Tacumshane today.\n\n==Tacumshane Windmill==\n[[File:Tacumshane Windmill.jpg|left|thumb|upright|Tacumshane Windmill]]\nThe windmill was built in 1846 by Nicolas Moran and was used until 1936, making it the last windmill in the Republic to work commercially. It was renovated in the 1950s. It is the oldest working windmill in Ireland. Access is managed via the nearby pub, \"The Millhouse Bar\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.goireland.com/wexford/tacumshane-windmill-attraction-windmills-id12366.htm|title=Tacumshane Windmill |website=www.goireland.com}}</ref>\n\n==Tacumshin Lake==\nTacumshin Lake or Lough as its locally known is 1100 acres in size and is designated a Special Protection Area (SPA) by the National Parks and Wildlife Services. Closed naturally since 1972, with a barrier of dune. A tidal system know locally as \u201cthe tunnel\u201d was constructed in the 1970s making the Lough tidal. A new system was built in the 1990s. Tachumshin Lake is a favourite with bird watchers. It attracts some rare American [[wader]]s in Autumn, as well as internationally important concentrations of [[Tundra swan|Bewick's swans]], [[Brent goose|Brent geese]], [[wigeon]], [[oystercatchers]], [[golden plover]] and [[lapwing]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.goireland.com/wexford/tacumshin-lake-lagoon-attraction-bird-watching-id12424.htm|title=Tacumshin Lake Lagoon Bird Watching |website=www.goireland.com}}</ref>\n\n==Transport==\n[[Bus \u00c9ireann]] route 378 serves Tacumshane on Fridays only and provides a link to and from [[Wexford]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.buseireann.ie/pdf/1202387058-378.pdf |title=Timetable - Route 378 |accessdate=2012-06-09 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120517023842/http://www.buseireann.ie/pdf/1202387058-378.pdf |archivedate=2012-05-17 }}</ref> Its terminus is at [[Wexford railway station]].\n{{clearleft}}\n==People==\n* [[John Barry (naval officer)]] He is often credited as \"The Father of the American Navy\". Barry was born in Tacumshane, County Wexford, Ireland and appointed a Captain in the Continental Navy on December 7, 1775.\n* [[John Meyler]] (born 1956 in Tacumshane, County Wexford) is an Irish [[hurling]] manager and former player. He played hurling with his local clubs Our Lady's Island and St. Finbarr's and with the Wexford and Cork senior inter-county teams from 1973 until 1987. Meyler later served as manager of Kerry, Wexford and Cork senior inter-county teams from 1990s through to today.\n\n==See also==\n* [[List of towns and villages in the Republic of Ireland|List of towns and villages in Ireland]]\n\n== References ==\n<!--- See [[Wikipedia:Footnotes]] on how to create references using  tags which will then appear here automatically -->\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.libraryireland.com/Lewis/LewisT/1-TACUMSHANE.php Tacumshane in from Sanuel Lewis's 1837 ''Topographical Dictionary of Ireland'']\n* [http://wexwind.com/heritage1.html History of Windmills in Wexford]\n* [https://meylersmillhouse.com/the-windmill/ A look inside the Tacumshane Windmill on Meyler's Millhouse Bar and Restaurant website]\n\n[[Category:Towns and villages in County Wexford]]\n", "text_old": "{{morefootnotes|date=February 2020}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=February 2020}}\n{{Use Irish English|date=February 2020}}\n{{Infobox settlement\n|name                   = Tacumshane\n|other_name             = {{pad top italic|Teach Coimse\u00e1in}}\n|settlement_type        = Village\n|image_skyline          = Tacumshane Windmill (geograph 6275920).jpg\n|image_caption          = Tacumshane Windmill \n|pushpin_map            = Ireland\n|pushpin_label_position = right\n|pushpin_map_caption    = Location in Ireland\n|subdivision_type       = Country\n|subdivision_name       = [[Republic of Ireland|Ireland]]\n|subdivision_type1      = [[Provinces of Ireland|Province]]\n|subdivision_name1      = [[Leinster]]\n|subdivision_type3      = [[Counties of Ireland|County]]\n|subdivision_name3      = [[County Wexford]]\n|established_title      = \n|established_date       = \n|unit_pref              = Metric\n|area_footnotes         = \n|area_total_km2         = \n|population_as_of       = \n|population_footnotes   = \n|population_total       = \n|population_urban       = \n|population_density_km2 = auto\n|timezone1              = [[West European Time|WET]] \n|utc_offset1            = +0\n|timezone1_DST          = [[Irish Standard Time|IST]] ([[Western European Summer Time|WEST]]) \n|utc_offset1_DST        = -1\n|coordinates            = {{coord|52.207|-6.41|dim:100000_region:IE|format=dms|display=inline,title}}\n|elevation_footnotes    = \n|elevation_m            = 24\n|blank_name             = [[Irish grid reference system|Irish Grid Reference]]\n|blank_info             = {{iem4ibx|T072076}}\n|website                = \n|footnotes              = \n}}\n\n'''Tacumshane''' ({{Irish place name|Teach Coimse\u00e1in}}) is a small village in the southeast of [[County Wexford]], [[Republic of Ireland|Ireland]]. It is located 15&nbsp;km south of Wexford town.\n\n==Name==\nThe official name of the village is Tacumshane. In [[Irish language|Irish]] it is called ''Teach Coimse\u00e1in'' (House of Se\u00e1n). The name of the village is often misspelled as \"Tacumshin\" as opposed to \"Tacumshane\". The lake and [[townland]] is spelled \"Tacumshin\", while the village and parish are spelled \"Tacumshane\". \nAbout two miles away is the townsland of Churchtown which was once called Tacumshane. It is where Tacumshane castle stood until it was demolished in 1984 by a local farmer. The Fence is the townsland located in the village of Tacumshane today.\n\n==Tacumshane Windmill==\n[[File:Tacumshane Windmill.jpg|left|thumb|upright|Tacumshane Windmill]]\nThe windmill was built in 1846 by Nicolas Moran and was used until 1936, making it the last windmill in the Republic to work commercially. It was renovated in the 1950s. It is the oldest working windmill in Ireland. Access is managed via the nearby pub, \"The Millhouse Bar\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.goireland.com/wexford/tacumshane-windmill-attraction-windmills-id12366.htm|title=Tacumshane Windmill |website=www.goireland.com}}</ref>\n\n==Tacumshin Lake==\nTacumshin Lake or Lough as its locally know is 1100 acres in size and is designated a Special Protection Area (SPA)by the National Parks and Wildlife Services. Closed naturally since 1972, with a barrier of dune. A tidal system know locally as \u201cthe tunnel\u201d was constructed in the 1970\u2019s making the Lough tidal. A new system was built in the 1990\u2019s. Tachumshin Lake is a favourite with bird watchers. It attracts some rare American [[wader]]s in Autumn, as well as internationally important concentrations of [[Tundra swan|Bewick's swans]], [[Brent goose|Brent geese]], [[wigeon]], [[oystercatchers]], [[golden plover]] and [[lapwing]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.goireland.com/wexford/tacumshin-lake-lagoon-attraction-bird-watching-id12424.htm|title=Tacumshin Lake Lagoon Bird Watching |website=www.goireland.com}}</ref>\n\n==Transport==\n[[Bus \u00c9ireann]] route 378 serves Tacumshane on Fridays only and provides a link to and from [[Wexford]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.buseireann.ie/pdf/1202387058-378.pdf |title=Timetable - Route 378 |accessdate=2012-06-09 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120517023842/http://www.buseireann.ie/pdf/1202387058-378.pdf |archivedate=2012-05-17 }}</ref> Its terminus is at [[Wexford railway station]].\n{{clearleft}}\n==People==\n* [[John Barry (naval officer)]] He is often credited as \"The Father of the American Navy\". Barry was born in Tacumshane, County Wexford, Ireland and appointed a Captain in the Continental Navy on December 7, 1775.\n* [[John Meyler]] (born 1956 in Tacumshane, County Wexford) is an Irish [[hurling]] manager and former player. He played hurling with his local clubs Our Lady's Island and St. Finbarr's and with the Wexford and Cork senior inter-county teams from 1973 until 1987. Meyler later served as manager of Kerry, Wexford and Cork senior inter-county teams from 1990s through to today.\n\n==See also==\n* [[List of towns and villages in the Republic of Ireland|List of towns and villages in Ireland]]\n\n== References ==\n<!--- See [[Wikipedia:Footnotes]] on how to create references using  tags which will then appear here automatically -->\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.libraryireland.com/Lewis/LewisT/1-TACUMSHANE.php Tacumshane in from Sanuel Lewis's 1837 ''Topographical Dictionary of Ireland'']\n* [http://wexwind.com/heritage1.html History of Windmills in Wexford]\n* [https://meylersmillhouse.com/the-windmill/ A look inside the Tacumshane Windmill on Meyler's Millhouse Bar and Restaurant website]\n\n[[Category:Towns and villages in County Wexford]]\n", "name_user": "Alistair1978", "label": "safe", "comment": "typos (viaWP:JWB)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Tacumshane"}
{"title_page": "Billy Elliot", "text_new": "{{about|the film|the musical|Billy Elliot the Musical|other uses|Billy Elliot (disambiguation)}}\n{{short description|2000 film directed by Stephen Daldry}}\n{{Use British English|date=November 2014}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=September 2013}}\n{{Infobox film\n| name           = Billy Elliot\n| image          = Billy Elliot movie.jpg\n| alt            = \n| caption        = US theatrical release poster\n| director       = [[Stephen Daldry]]\n| producer       = {{ubl|[[Greg Brenman]]|Jon Finn}}\n| writer         = [[Lee Hall (playwright)|Lee Hall]]\n| starring       = {{Plainlist|\n* [[Julie Walters]]\n* [[Gary Lewis (actor)|Gary Lewis]]\n* [[Jamie Bell]]\n* [[Jamie Draven]]\n* [[Adam Cooper (dancer)|Adam Cooper]]}}<!--As per poster block, Bell is credited below Walters and Lewis-->\n| music          = [[Stephen Warbeck]]\n| cinematography = Brian Tufano\n| editing        = John Wilson\n| studio         = {{ubl|[[BBC Films]]|[[Tiger Aspect Productions|Tiger Aspect Pictures]]|[[Working Title Films]]}}\n| distributor    = [[United International Pictures]] ([[Universal Studios|Universal Pictures]])\n| released       = {{Film date|df=y|2000|09|29}} (United Kingdom)\n| runtime        = 110 minutes<!--Theatrical runtime: 110:09--><ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.bbfc.co.uk/releases/billy-elliot-1970-1 | title=Billy Elliot (15) | publisher=[[British Board of Film Classification]] | date=21 August 2000 | accessdate=7 November 2014 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141107210122/http://www.bbfc.co.uk/releases/billy-elliot-1970-1 | archive-date=7 November 2014 | url-status=live }}</ref>\n| country        = United Kingdom\n| language       = English\n| budget         = $5 million<ref name=\"box off mojo\">{{cite web | url=https://www.boxofficemojo.com/title/tt0249462/?ref_=bo_se_r_1 | title=Billy Elliot \u2013 Box Office Mojo | publisher=Box Office Mojo | date=2020-01-03 | accessdate=2020-01-03}}</ref>\n| gross          = $109.3 million<ref name=\"box off mojo\" />\n}}\n'''''Billy Elliot''''' is a 2000 dance [[Drama (film and television)|drama film]] directed by [[Stephen Daldry]] and written by [[Lee Hall (playwright)|Lee Hall]]. Set in [[County Durham]], [[North East England|England]] during the [[UK miners' strike (1984\u20131985)|1984\u201385 miners' strike]], the film is about a working-class boy who discovers his passion for [[ballet]], despite his father's objection and the [[Western stereotype of the male ballet dancer|negative stereotype]] associated of being a male ballet dancer. The film stars [[Jamie Bell]] as 11-year-old Billy, [[Gary Lewis (actor)|Gary Lewis]] as his father, [[Jamie Draven]] as Billy's older brother, and [[Julie Walters]] as his ballet teacher.\n\nAdapted from a play called ''Dancer'' by Lee Hall, development on the film began in 1999. Around 2,000 boys were considered for the role of Billy before Bell was eventually chosen for the role. Filming began in the North of England in August 1999. [[Greg Brenman]] and Jon Finn served as producers, while [[Stephen Warbeck]] composed the film's score. ''Billy Elliot'' is a co-production between [[BBC Films]], [[Tiger Aspect Productions|Tiger Aspect Pictures]] and [[Working Title Films]].\n\nThe film premiered at the [[2000 Cannes Film Festival]], and then began a wider theatrical release on 29 September 2000 by [[Universal Pictures]]. ''Billy Elliot'' received positive critical response and commercial success, earning $109.3 million worldwide on a $5 million budget. At the [[British Academy Film Awards|2001 British Academy Film Awards]], the film won three of thirteen award nominations. The film also earned three [[Academy Awards|Academy Award]] nominations, including for [[Academy Award for Best Director|Best Director]], [[Academy Award for Best Original Screenplay|Best Original Screenplay]] and [[Academy Award for Best Supporting Actress|Best Actress in a Supporting Role]]. In 2001, the film was adapted into a novel by [[Melvin Burgess]]. The story was also adapted for the [[West End theatre|West End]] stage as ''[[Billy Elliot the Musical]]'' in 2005; it opened in Australia in 2007 and on [[Broadway theatre|Broadway]] in 2008.\n\n== Plot ==\nIn 1984, Billy Elliot, an 11-year-old from the fictional Everington in County Durham, England, loves to dance and has hopes of becoming a professional ballet dancer. Billy lives with his widowed father, Jackie, and older brother, Tony, both coal miners out on [[UK miners' strike (1984\u201385)|strike]] (the latter being the union bully), and also his maternal grandmother, who has [[Alzheimer's disease]] and once aspired to be a professional dancer.\n\nBilly's father sends him to the gym to learn boxing, but Billy dislikes the sport. He happens to see a ballet class that is using the gym while their usual basement studio is temporarily being used as a [[soup kitchen]] for the striking miners. Unknown to Jackie, Billy joins the ballet class. When Jackie discovers this, he forbids Billy to take any more ballet. But, passionate about dancing, Billy secretly continues lessons with the help of his dance teacher, Sandra Wilkinson.[[File:Jamie Bell by Gage Skidmore.jpg|thumb|[[Jamie Bell]] (pictured in 2015) received acclaim for his performance as Billy.|216x216px]]\n\nMrs. Wilkinson believes that Billy is talented enough to study at the [[Royal Ballet School]] in London, but due to Tony's arrest during a clash between police and striking miners, Billy misses the audition. Mrs. Wilkinson tells Jackie about the missed opportunity, but fearing that Billy will be considered to be gay, both Jackie and Tony are outraged at the prospect of him becoming a professional ballet dancer.\n\nOver Christmas, Billy learns his best friend Michael is gay. Billy is supportive of his friend. Later, Jackie catches Billy dancing in the gym and realises his son is truly gifted; he resolves to do whatever it takes to help Billy attain his dream. Mrs. Wilkinson tries to persuade Jackie to let her pay for the audition, but he replies that Billy is his son and he does not need charity. Jackie attempts to [[strikebreaker|cross the picket line]] to pay for the trip to London, but Tony stops him. Instead, his fellow miners and the neighbourhood raise some money and Jackie pawns Billy's mother's jewellery to cover the cost, and Jackie takes him to London to audition.\n\nAlthough very nervous, Billy performs well, but he punches another boy in frustration at the audition, fearing that he has ruined his chances of attaining his dream. He is rebuked by the review board, but when asked what it feels like when he is dancing, he struggles for words but describes it as being \"like electricity\". Seemingly rejected, Billy returns home with his father. Sometime later, the Royal Ballet School sends him a letter of acceptance, coinciding with the end of the miners' strike, and he leaves home for London.\n\nIn 1998, 25-year-old Billy takes the stage to perform the Swan in [[Matthew Bourne]]'s ''[[Swan Lake (Bourne)|Swan Lake]]'', as Jackie, Tony, and Michael watch from the audience; his father visibly moved by the performance.\n\n==Cast==\n{{div col}}\n* [[Jamie Bell]] as Billy Elliot \n** [[Adam Cooper (dancer)|Adam Cooper]] as Billy aged 25\n* [[Julie Walters]] as Sandra Wilkinson\n* [[Gary Lewis (actor)|Gary Lewis]] as Jackie Elliot\n* [[Jamie Draven]] as Tony Elliot\n* [[Jean Heywood]] as Grandma\n* [[Stuart Wells]] as Michael Caffrey\n** Merryn Owen as Michael aged 25\n* Nicola Blackwell as Debbie Wilkinson\n* Colin Maclachlan as Tom Wilkinson\n* [[Mike Elliott (comedian)|Mike Elliott]] as George Watson\n* Billy Fane as Mr Braithwaite\n* Janine Birkett as Jenny Elliot\n* [[Charlie Hardwick]] as Sheila Briggs\n* [[Matthew James Thomas]] as Simon\n* [[Stephen Mangan]] as Dr. Crane\n* [[Patrick Malahide]] as Royal Ballet School principal\n* [[Barbara Leigh-Hunt]] as Royal Ballet School vice-principal\n* [[Neil North]] as Royal Ballet School tutor\n* [[Lee Williams (actor)|Lee Williams]] as Royal Ballet School tutor\n{{div col end}}\n\n==Production==\n\n=== Development ===\n[[File:Avon Street, Easington Colliery.jpg|thumb|Terraced homes on Avon Street were used for filming, where Andrew and Alnwick Streets once stood. |alt=|195x195px]]Lee Hall developed ''Billy Elliot'' from his play ''Dancer'', which premiered as a rehearsed reading in 1998 at the [[Live Theatre Company|Live Theatre]] in [[Newcastle upon Tyne]].<ref>{{cite news |title=Lee Hall interview: Why Lee will always love Live Theatre |date=17 June 2014 |url=http://www.thejournal.co.uk/culture/culture-news/lee-hall-interview-lee-always-7279467 |author=The Journal |work=[[The Journal (newspaper)|The Journal]] |accessdate=6 January 2015 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150106235237/http://www.thejournal.co.uk/culture/culture-news/lee-hall-interview-lee-always-7279467 |archive-date=6 January 2015 |url-status=live }}</ref> He was heavily influenced by photographer [[Sirkka-Liisa Konttinen]]'s book ''Step by Step'', about a dancing school in nearby [[North Shields]]. Writing in 2009, Hall said that \"almost every frame of ''Billy Elliot'' was influenced by ''Step by Step'' ... as every member of the design team carried around their own copy.\"<ref>{{cite book |title=Byker Revisited |first=Sirkka-Liisa |last=Konttinen |page=vi |publisher=Northumbria Press |isbn=978-1904794424 |year=2009}}</ref>\n\nHall met with director Stephen Daldry, who was working at the [[Royal Court Theatre]] at the time. At first, Daldry was not convinced with the script, but said, \"I liked the emotional honesty of ''Billy Elliot.'' Also Lee writes brilliant kids. And there's a series of themes in it I rather enjoyed: Grief; finding means of self-identification through some sort of creative act, in this case dance; and the miner's strike itself.\"<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.indiewire.com/2000/10/interview-stephen-daldry-dances-to-success-with-billy-elliot-81337/|title=Interview: Stephen Daldry Dances to Success with \"Billy Elliot\"|last=Indiewire|last2=Indiewire|date=2000-10-17|website=IndieWire|language=en|access-date=2020-01-02|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200102200205/https://www.indiewire.com/2000/10/interview-stephen-daldry-dances-to-success-with-billy-elliot-81337/|archive-date=2 January 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> [[Working Title Films]] approached Daldry to become director and he accepted the offer. The [[BBC]] financed the project.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://pubs.socialistreviewindex.org.uk/sr247/mitchell.htm|title=Interview: Lee Hall, screenwriter of Billy Elliot|website=pubs.socialistreviewindex.org.uk|access-date=2020-01-02|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190704151046/http://pubs.socialistreviewindex.org.uk/sr247/mitchell.htm|archive-date=4 July 2019|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n=== Casting ===\nThousands of boys were considered for the lead role. The producers were looking for a boy in a specific geographical area with a dance background. Jamie Bell had about seven auditions in total before eventually in mid-1999, it was announced that he would play the lead role in the film.<ref name=\":0\" /> [[Peter Darling]], the film's choreographer, worked with Bell for \"eight hours a day for three months, finding out what drove him as a dancer.\" Julie Walters accepted the role of Sandra Wilkinson. Walters called the script \"moving\", explaining, \"It was a diamond in the sand ... I loved the character, and the fact that she was disappointed on every level possible. She was so grim and jaded. Her relationship with the boy was so unusual\".<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/film/2001/may/14/features|title=Julie Walters: An actress in her prime|last=Mottram|first=James|date=2001-05-14|work=The Guardian|access-date=2020-01-02|language=en-GB|issn=0261-3077|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200102200204/https://www.theguardian.com/film/2001/may/14/features|archive-date=2 January 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nIn preparation for filming, Gary Lewis met with miners \"which helped a lot\".<ref name=\":7\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.erasingclouds.com/02lewis.html|title=The Good Times: films, awards and Italy. An interview with actor Gary Lewis.|last=Battista|first=Anna|date=2001|website=www.erasingclouds.com|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-04-03}}</ref> Lewis stated that his own personal experience of the miners' strike made the role enjoyable. \"My family and I were very active in supporting the miners: I stood in picket lines, I raised money for the miners and I was involved in the whole campaign to stop ... closing the pits. Basically, it was the state that launched a complete attack on a section of the work force, a section of the working class. Lots of people responded with solidarity and that was a key element in the script: solidarity working at different levels, the collective solidarity, the economic solidarity.\"<ref name=\":7\" />\n\n===Filming===\n[[Principal photography]] last seven weeks, beginning in August 1999.<ref name=\":0\" /><ref name=\":8\">{{Cite web|url=http://cinema.com/articles/160/billy-elliot-production-notes.phtml|title=Billy Elliot : Production Notes|website=cinema.com|access-date=2020-04-03}}</ref> Most of the film, including the interior of the Elliot home at 5 Alnwick Street, was shot on location in the [[Easington Colliery]] area, with the producers using over 400 locals as extras.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.theguardian.com/stage/2014/sep/28/billy-elliot-musical-easington-village-screening |title=Village shares its Billy Elliot stories at live screening of West End show |work=[[The Guardian]] |publisher=Guardian News and Media |date=28 September 2014 |accessdate=9 April 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180410072410/https://www.theguardian.com/stage/2014/sep/28/billy-elliot-musical-easington-village-screening |archive-date=10 April 2018 |url-status=live }}</ref> The mining scenes were filmed at the [[Ellington, Northumberland|Ellington]] and [[Lynemouth]] Colliery in [[Northumberland]], with some filming in [[Dawdon]], [[Middlesbrough]] and Newcastle upon Tyne.<ref name=\"bbctyne_feature\">{{cite web|url=http://www.bbc.co.uk/tyne/content/articles/2006/04/07/hollywood_on_tyne_billy_elliot_04_2006_feature.shtml|title=Feature: Billy Elliot|date=17 October 2006|work=BBC Tyne|publisher=[[BBC]]|accessdate=6 January 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110629123134/http://www.bbc.co.uk/tyne/content/articles/2006/04/07/hollywood_on_tyne_billy_elliot_04_2006_feature.shtml|archive-date=29 June 2011|url-status=live}}</ref> Andrew Street and Alnwick Street, where the characters live, were two of several streets demolished in 2003 after becoming [[Urban decay|derelict]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/uk_news/england/2386705.stm|title=Billy Elliott's house to be bulldozed|last=|first=|date=1 November 2002|website=BBC|publisher=[[BBC]]|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180410074943/http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/uk_news/england/2386705.stm|archive-date=10 April 2018|accessdate=9 April 2018}}</ref> The cemetery scene was filmed at Lynemouth Cemetery.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.thefreelibrary.com/Dying+for+someone+to+take+care+of+cemetery%3B+PLEA+FOR+LANDOWNERS+TO...-a0181664854 |title=Dying for someone to take care of cemetery; Plea for landowners to clean up overgrown graveyard |work=[[Evening Chronicle]] |publisher=[[Trinity Mirror]] |date=22 July 2008 |accessdate=9 April 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180410072235/https://www.thefreelibrary.com/Dying+for+someone+to+take+care+of+cemetery%3B+PLEA+FOR+LANDOWNERS+TO...-a0181664854 |archive-date=10 April 2018 |url-status=live }}</ref> School scenes were filmed in [[Langley Park, County Durham|Langley Park]] Primary School.<ref name=\"locations\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.movie-locations.com/movies/b/Billy-Elliot.php|title=Filming Locations for Billy Elliot (2000)|website=The Worldwide Guide to Movie Locations|access-date=2020-01-02|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200101130142/http://www.movie-locations.com/movies/b/Billy-Elliot.php|archive-date=1 January 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> Other filming locations include the Green Drive Railway Viaduct in [[Seaham]], [[Tees Transporter Bridge]], [[New Wardour Castle]] and [[Theatre Royal Haymarket|Theatre Royal]] in [[Haymarket, London|Haymarket]].<ref name=\"locations\" /><ref name=\"reel\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.reelstreets.com/films/billy-elliot/|title=Reelstreets {{!}} Billy Elliot|website=www.reelstreets.com|access-date=2020-01-02|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200101130143/https://www.reelstreets.com/films/billy-elliot/|archive-date=1 January 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nDaldry remarked in an interview, \"The shooting schedule was a nightmare; we only had seven weeks. Kids can only work nine to five and you can\u2019t work Saturdays. And the kid had to dance the whole time. So it was tight.\"<ref name=\":0\" /> Producer Jon Finn, spoke of the difficulties of seeking filming locations; \"We didn't realise how hard it would be to find working [[Open-pit mining|pits]].\"<ref name=\":8\" />\n\n==Music==\n{{Infobox album\n| name         = Billy Elliot\n| type         = soundtrack\n| artist       = Various artists\n| cover        = \n| alt          = \n| released     = 11 March 2002\n| recorded     = 2000\n| venue        = \n| studio       = \n| genre        = [[Punk rock]], [[Glam rock]], [[Pop music|Pop]], [[New wave]]\n| length       = 51:34\n| label        = [[Polydor Records]]\n| producer     = Various artists\n| prev_title   = \n| prev_year    = \n| next_title   = \n| next_year    = \n| misc         = {{Singles\n | name        = Billy Elliot: Original Motion Picture Soundtrack\n | type        = soundtrack\n | single1     = [[I Believe (Stephen Gately song)|I Believe]]\n | single1date = 14 October 2000\n}}\n}}\n[[Stephen Warbeck]] scored the [[incidental music]] for the film. [[Polydor Records]] released the soundtrack on 11 March 2002, which includes several well-known glam rock and punk songs from [[T. Rex (band)|T. Rex]] and [[The Clash]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.allmusic.com/album/release/billy-elliot-mr0001347394|title=Billy Elliot \u2013 Original Soundtrack {{!}} Release Info|website=AllMusic|language=en-us|access-date=2019-12-27|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191227160839/https://www.allmusic.com/album/release/billy-elliot-mr0001347394|archive-date=27 December 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> The soundtrack also contains pieces of dialogue from the film.\n\n{{Track listing\n| headline = Original Motion Picture Soundtrack\n| title1 = Cosmic Dancer\n| music1 = [[T. Rex (band)|T. Rex]]\n| length1 = 4:28\n| title2 = Boys Play Football\n| music2 = Jamie Bell & Gary Lewis\n| length2 = 4:24\n| title3 = [[Bang a Gong (Get It On)]]\n| music3 = T. Rex\n| length3 = 4:24\n| title4 = Mother's Letter\n| music4 = Jamie Bell & Julie Walters\n| length4 = 5:22\n| title5 = [[I Believe (Stephen Gately song)|I Believe]]\n| music5 = [[Stephen Gately]]\n| length5 = 3:27\n| title6 = [[Town Called Malice]]\n| music6 = [[The Jam]]\n| length6 = 2:53\n| title7 = The Sun Will Come Out\n| music7 = Jamie Bell, Nicole Blackwell & Julie Walters\n| length7 = 0:50\n| title8 = [[I Love to Boogie]]\n| music8 = T. Rex\n| length8 = 2:11\n| title9 = Burning Up\n| music9 = [[Eagle-Eye Cherry]]\n| length9 = 4:14\n| title10 = Royal Ballet School\n| music10 = Jamie Bell & Julie Walters\n| length10 = 1:11\n| title11 = [[London Calling]]\n| music11 = [[The Clash]]\n| length11 = 3:20\n| title12 = Children of the Revolution\n| music12 = T. Rex\n| length12 = 4:44\n| title13 = Audition Panel\n| music13 = Jamie Bell & Barbara Leigh Hunt\n| length13 = 0:33\n| title14 = Shout to the Top!\n| music14 = [[The Style Council]]\n| length14 = 4:14\n| title15 = Walls Come Tumbling Down!\n| music15 = The Style Council\n| length15 = 3:21\n| title16 = Ride a White Swan\n| music16 = T. Rex\n| length16 = 2:14\n| title17 = Cosmic Dancer (Reprise)\n| music17 = T. Rex\n| length17 = 4:27\n| total_length = 51:34\n| all_writing = \n}}\n\n==Reception==\n\n=== Box office ===\n[[File:Billy Elliot lorry London.JPG|thumbnail|Advertisement for the ''Billy Elliot'' musical on a lorry in London.]]\n''Billy Elliot'' premiered on 19 May at the [[2000 Cannes Film Festival]] under the title ''Dancer''.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.thetimes.co.uk/article/billy-elliot-and-the-miners-strike-97mfqfh3kw7|title=Billy Elliot and the miners' strike|date=2005-03-13|work=The Times|access-date=2020-01-02|language=en|issn=0140-0460|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200102205048/https://www.thetimes.co.uk/article/billy-elliot-and-the-miners-strike-97mfqfh3kw7|archive-date=2 January 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> It was later decided to re-title the film ''Billy Elliot'' to avoid confusion with ''[[Dancer in the Dark]]'', another film at Cannes that year. ''Billy Elliot'' was theatrically released on 29 September 2000 in the United Kingdom by Universal Pictures and [[Focus Features]]. In the United States, the film was released on 13 October 2001.<ref name=\":9\" /> Against expectations, the film earned a worldwide total of $109,280,263.<ref name=\":9\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.boxofficemojo.com/title/tt0249462/?ref_=bo_se_r_1|title=Billy Elliot|website=Box Office Mojo|access-date=2019-12-25}}</ref> [[Universal Studios Home Entertainment|Universal Home Entertainment]] released ''Billy Elliot'' on [[VHS]] on 20 April 2001 and on [[Blu-ray Disc|Blu-ray]] on 10 January 2012.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.the-numbers.com/movie/Billy-Elliot|title=Billy Elliot (2000) \u2013 Financial Information|website=The Numbers|access-date=2020-04-03}}</ref><ref>{{Citation|title=Billy Elliot Blu-ray Release Date January 10, 2012|url=https://www.blu-ray.com/movies/Billy-Elliot-Blu-ray/33802/|access-date=2020-04-03}}</ref>\n\n=== Critical response ===\nOn review aggregator website [[Rotten Tomatoes]], the film holds an approval rating of 85% based on 117 reviews, with an average rating of 7.3/10. The site's critical consensus reads: \"''Billy Elliot'' is a charming movie that can evoke both laughter and tears.\"<ref name=\"tomatoes\">{{cite web |url=https://www.rottentomatoes.com/m/billy_elliot |title=Billy Elliot (2000) |work=[[Rotten Tomatoes]] |publisher=[[Fandango (company)|Fandango Media]] |accessdate=9 April 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171127040601/https://www.rottentomatoes.com/m/billy_elliot/ |archive-date=27 November 2017 |url-status=live }}</ref> At [[Metacritic]], the film has a weighted average score of 74 out of 100, based on 34 critics, indicating \"generally favourable reviews\".<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.metacritic.com/movie/billy-elliot |title=Billy Elliot Reviews |work=[[Metacritic]] |publisher=[[CBS Interactive]] |accessdate=9 April 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180505230815/http://www.metacritic.com/movie/billy-elliot |archive-date=5 May 2018 |url-status=live }}</ref> Audiences polled by [[CinemaScore]] gave the film an average grade of \"A\u2013\" on an A+ to F scale.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.cinemascore.com/|title=CinemaScore|date=|website=Cinemascore|language=en-US|others=(Type 'Billy Elliot' in the search box)|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180102130540/https://www.cinemascore.com/|archive-date=2 January 2018|access-date=2020-01-02}}</ref>\n\nFilm critic [[Roger Ebert]] gave the film three out of four stars, calling the film \"much parable and fantasy as it is realistic\". He said Bell's performance was \"engaging\", Lewis was \"convincing\" and Walters was \"spirited and colourful\".<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.rogerebert.com/reviews/billy-elliot-2000/ |title=Billy Elliot |last=Ebert |first=Roger |authorlink=Roger Ebert |work=RogerEbert.com |publisher=Ebert Digital LLC |accessdate=9 April 2018 |date=13 October 2000 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171227212916/https://www.rogerebert.com/reviews/billy-elliot-2000 |archive-date=27 December 2017 |url-status=live }}</ref> Peter Bradshaw of ''[[The Guardian]]'' praised the film saying, \"This is a film with a lot of charm, a lot of humour and a lot of heart. Daldry's direction and the screenplay by Lee Hall distinguish themselves further in the discreet, intelligent way ... ''Billy Elliot'' has a freshness that makes it a pleasure to watch; it's a very emphatic success\".<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/film/2000/sep/29/1|title=Billy Elliot|last=Staff|first=Guardian|date=2000-09-29|work=The Guardian|access-date=2019-12-26|language=en-GB|issn=0261-3077|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191229004813/https://www.theguardian.com/film/2000/sep/29/1|archive-date=29 December 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> David Rooney of ''[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]'' also praised the cast, writing, \"Relationships between all the characters are well observed \u2014 the father and his sons, the two brothers, and Billy and his grandmother, his friend Michael and jaded Mrs. Wilkinson \u2014 all of them yielding sweet, unforced feel-good moments\". Rooney also praised the cinematography, visuals and soundtrack in showing Billy's rebelliousness.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://variety.com/2000/film/reviews/billy-elliot-4-1200462157/|title=Billy Elliot|last=Rooney|first=David|last2=Rooney|first2=David|date=2000-05-22|website=Variety|language=en|access-date=2019-12-26|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191226180206/https://variety.com/2000/film/reviews/billy-elliot-4-1200462157/|archive-date=26 December 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> O'Sullivan in ''[[The Independent]]'' wrote the cast are \"near perfect\", adding the film is a \"slice of escapism as you could wish for\".<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.independent.co.uk/arts-entertainment/films/reviews/first-impressions-billy-elliot-2000-1027341.html|title=First Impressions: Billy Elliot (2000)|date=2008-11-21|website=The Independent|language=en|access-date=2020-01-02|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200102223256/https://www.independent.co.uk/arts-entertainment/films/reviews/first-impressions-billy-elliot-2000-1027341.html|archive-date=2 January 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> William Gallagher from the BBC gave the film five out of five stars, writing, \"It's a simple tale but one that is extremely well told and acted. Fittingly for a story about dance, it doesn't put a foot wrong and is engrossing, funny, very sad, very moving and very uplifting.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.bbc.co.uk/films/2000/09/11/billy_elliot_review.shtml|title=BBC \u2013 Films \u2013 Billy Elliot|last=|first=|date=|publisher=BBC|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171201015718/http://www.bbc.co.uk/films/2000/09/11/billy_elliot_review.shtml|archive-date=1 December 2017|access-date=2020-01-02}}</ref>\n\nSome critics gave a mixed response. [[Time Out (magazine)|''Time Out'']] believes that \"Daldry overuses the dance as a metaphor for escape and frustration, and choreographer Peter Darling's grandstanding ballet numbers sit a little uneasily, given the realist comedy pitch\".<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.timeout.com/london/film/billy-elliot|title=Billy Elliot|website=Time Out London|language=en|access-date=2019-12-26|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190707225240/https://www.timeout.com/london/film/billy-elliot|archive-date=7 July 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> [[A. O. Scott]] of ''[[The New York Times]]'' notes that there were \"patches of thinness and predictability\", and that \"the first half seems to acknowledge its own triteness\". However, he compliments the pacing of the scenes and the actors who \"inhabit their roles like second-hand suits\".<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2000/10/13/movies/film-review-escaping-a-miner-s-life-for-a-career-in-ballet.html|title=Film Review; Escaping a Miner's Life For a Career in Ballet|last=Scott|first=A. O.|date=2000-10-13|work=The New York Times|access-date=2019-12-26|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191226180206/https://www.nytimes.com/2000/10/13/movies/film-review-escaping-a-miner-s-life-for-a-career-in-ballet.html|archive-date=26 December 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> Mark Holcomb, writing for ''[[IndieWire]]'', took issue with the \"odd, unsuccessful mix of theatrical whimsy and social realism\", and a dance scene which he describes as a \"cringe-inducing \u201980s-style music video routine\".<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.indiewire.com/2000/10/review-mixed-steps-pleasing-and-predictable-billy-elliot-81347/|title=Review: Mixed Steps, Pleasing and Predictable \"Billy Elliot\"|last=Indiewire|last2=Indiewire|date=2000-10-12|website=IndieWire|language=en|access-date=2020-01-02|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200102223244/https://www.indiewire.com/2000/10/review-mixed-steps-pleasing-and-predictable-billy-elliot-81347/|archive-date=2 January 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n=== Themes ===\nPoverty and [[social class]] have been seen as major themes of the film. Author Rebecca Mahon observed the film has a realistic setting; the early scenes emphasising the miners' strike, the death of Billy's mother and the family's financial situation.<ref>{{Cite book|title=Billy Elliot|last=Mahon, Rebecca.|date=2003|publisher=Pascal Press|others=Daldry, Stephen.|isbn=1-74125-037-4|location=Glebe, NSW|pages=14|oclc=224040491}}</ref> Daldry adds, \"It doesn't matter where you are in the world, people understand the idea that you're part of an industrial, working class group that is being discarded. And its question\u2014of what happens to communities devastated by de-industrialisation and [[Privatization|privatisation]]\". In addition to social class, Daldry states that the film is about finding a voice\u2014\"someone trying to express himself or herself\".<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://qz.com/1096401/director-stephen-daldry-on-billy-elliot-the-meaning-and-message-behind-the-films-most-memorable-scene/|title=Why Billy Elliot's most memorable scene still resonates across the world|last=Mohdin|first=Aamna|website=Quartz|language=en|access-date=2020-01-03|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200103120809/https://qz.com/1096401/director-stephen-daldry-on-billy-elliot-the-meaning-and-message-behind-the-films-most-memorable-scene/|archive-date=3 January 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> Koller-Alonso writes that gender differences are expressed by showing girls attending ballet classes, while their male counterparts are having [[boxing]] lessons. Homosexuality, a taboo subject in the 1980s, as well as [[police brutality]] are depicted and explored in the film.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://theculturetrip.com/europe/united-kingdom/england/london/articles/what-billy-elliot-taught-us-about-british-history/|title=What Billy Elliot Taught Us About British History|last=Koller-Alonso|first=Sara|website=Culture Trip|access-date=2020-01-03|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200103120811/https://theculturetrip.com/europe/united-kingdom/england/london/articles/what-billy-elliot-taught-us-about-british-history/|archive-date=3 January 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n===Accolades===\n{| class=\"sortable wikitable plainrowheaders awards-table\" style=\"table-layout: fixed; margin-right: 0; \"\n|+\n! scope=\"col\" |Award\n! scope=\"col\" |Category\n! scope=\"col\" |Recipients)\n! scope=\"col\" |Result\n! scope=\"col\" class=\"unsortable\" |Ref(s)\n|-\n| rowspan=\"3\" |[[Academy Awards]]\n|[[Academy Award for Best Original Screenplay|Best Original Screenplay]]\n| {{sort|Daldry|Stephen Daldry}}\n|{{nom}}\n|<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/entertainment/1168138.stm|title=Walters leads UK Oscars charge|date=2001-02-13|access-date=2020-01-03|language=en-GB|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200103101155/http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/entertainment/1168138.stm|archive-date=3 January 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n|-\n|[[Academy Award for Best Director|Best Director]]\n|{{sort|Hall|Lee Hall}}\n|{{nom}}\n|<ref name=\":1\" />\n|-\n|[[Academy Award for Best Supporting Actress|Best Actress in a Supporting Role]]\n|{{sort|Walters|Julie Walters}}\n|{{nom}}\n|<ref name=\":1\" />\n|-\n|[[American Cinema Editors]]\n|Best Edited Dramatic Feature Film\n|\n|{{nom}}\n|<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://cinemajam.com/mag/interviews/john-wilson|title=John Wilson Interview \u2013 \"Billy Elliot\" and \"Downton Abbey\" editor|date=2017-01-23|website=The Spread|access-date=2020-01-03|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200103111026/http://cinemajam.com/mag/interviews/john-wilson|archive-date=3 January 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n|-\n|[[Art Directors Guild]]\n|Feature Film\n|\n|{{nom}}\n|<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://adg.org/awards/adg/winners/2001/|title=ADG Awards Winner & Nominees|website=adg.org|language=en|access-date=2020-01-03|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190805211840/https://adg.org/awards/adg/winners/2001/|archive-date=5 August 2019|url-status=live}}</ref>\n|-\n|[[Australian Film Institute]]\n|Best Foreign Film\n|\n|{{nom}}\n|<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.aacta.org/aacta-awards/past-awards/|title=Past Awards|date=|website=www.aacta.org|language=en-AU|others=Click on 'Additional Awards'|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191225184513/https://www.aacta.org/aacta-awards/past-awards/|archive-date=25 December 2019|access-date=2020-01-03}}</ref>\n|-\n| rowspan=\"12\" |[[British Academy of Film and Television Arts]]\n|[[BAFTA Award for Best Film]]\n|\n| style=\"background: #99FF99; color: black; vertical-align: middle; text-align: center; \" class=\"yes table-yes2\" |Won\n|<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.irishtimes.com/news/billy-elliot-takes-three-awards-at-baftas-1.285198|title='Billy Elliot' takes three awards at Baftas|website=The Irish Times|language=en|ac